# Computing top categories in terms of sales and profit and presenting them graphically

s = dataset.groupby("Category").Sales.sum()

p = dataset.groupby("Category").Profit.sum()

plt.style.use('seaborn')
s.plot(kind = 'bar',figsize = (12,6),fontsize = 16, color='green')
p.plot(kind = 'bar',figsize = (12,6),fontsize = 16,color='yellow')
plt.xlabel('Category',fontsize = 16)
plt.ylabel('Profits',fontsize = 16)
plt.title("Category Sales vs Profit",fontsize = 16)
plt.show()

In [45]:
# Checking the dependency of sales,profit and discount

plt.style.use('seaborn')
dataset.plot(kind = "scatter",figsize = (10,5), x = "Sales", y= "Profit", c = "Discount", s = 20,fontsize = 16, colormap = "viridis")
plt.ylabel('Total Profits',fontsize = 16)
plt.title("Interdependency of Sales,Profits and Discounts",fontsize = 16)

plt.show()

The graph clearly shows that if we give more Discount on our products sales increases but profit decreases.¶

Points to be noted:¶

1. The features Profit and Discounts are highly related.¶
2. Considering the sub-categories sales of tables should be minimized.¶
3. Over Less quantity of products also the sales were high.¶
4. We should concentrate on the states like 'New York' and 'California' to make more profits.¶
